  <a href="#1" id="1">
   The Soviet Union said today that a united Germany can join NATO after a five-year transition period during which all Soviet and U.S. troops would leave the country.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Shevardnadze made the proposal as he met with U.S.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III and their counterparts from Britain, France and the two German states.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   It also said that within six months of unification, all Western troops should leave West Berlin, which remains technically under military occupation by the United States, France and Britian.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   There are about 380,000 Soviet troops in East Germany, while a quarter-million U.S. troops are stationed in West Germany along with tens of thousands of British and French soldiers.
  </a>
